rpm --import https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.key
curl -Lo /etc/yum.repos.d/corretto.repo https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.repo
yum install -y java-17-amazon-corretto-devel --nogpgcheck


1) rpm --import https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.key
What it does

This command imports Amazon Corretto’s GPG key into your system.

Simple meaning

Your server is saying:

“Before I install software from Amazon Corretto repo, let me store Amazon’s signature key so I can verify whether the package is really from them.”

Real-world example

Suppose a courier brings a parcel.

Before accepting it, you check:

Is it really from Amazon?

Is the seal genuine?

That GPG key is like the official company seal/sample signature used to verify packages.

Word breakdown

rpm → package manager tool used in RHEL/CentOS/Amazon Linux type systems

--import → import a key

https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.key → location of Amazon’s public key

2) curl -Lo /etc/yum.repos.d/corretto.repo https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.repo
What it does

This downloads the Corretto repository configuration file and saves it into the yum repo folder.

Simple meaning

You are telling your server:

“Here is the address of Amazon Corretto software store. Save it, so from now on you know where to download Corretto packages.”

Real-world example

Imagine your phone doesn’t know a new grocery shop exists.

You save:

shop name

shop address

contact details

Now your phone knows where to order from.

That .repo file is basically the saved address/details of the software shop.

Word breakdown

curl → used to download content from a URL

-L → follow redirects

-o → save output to a file

/etc/yum.repos.d/corretto.repo → destination file path where yum stores repo definitions

https://yum.corretto.aws/corretto.repo → repo file URL

Why this location?

Because /etc/yum.repos.d/ is the standard place where yum keeps repository definitions.

3) yum install -y java-17-amazon-corretto-devel --nogpgcheck
What it does

This installs Amazon Corretto JDK 17 Development package.

Simple meaning

You are telling yum:

“Go to the configured repositories, find Java 17 Corretto development package, and install it automatically.”

Real-world example

Now that:

you trust the shop

you know the shop address

you finally place the order:

“Send me Java 17 development kit.”

Word breakdown

yum install → install a package

-y → automatically answer “yes” for prompts

java-17-amazon-corretto-devel → package name

--nogpgcheck → do not verify package signature during installation

Important point about --nogpgcheck

This part is a little odd here.

You already imported the GPG key in step 1.

So normally, the system should verify package signatures properly.
But --nogpgcheck says:

“Install it even if signature verification is skipped.”

Simple meaning

It is like saying:

“I know the shop, but don’t check the parcel seal this time.”

In real world

That is less secure.

Better understanding

With GPG check → safer

With --nogpgcheck → less secure, often used in temporary/testing situations or when there is some repo/signature issue

So in most cases, if repo is configured correctly, you should prefer:

yum install -y java-17-amazon-corretto-devel

without --nogpgcheck.

Overall flow in one easy story

Imagine your Linux server is a company employee.

Step 1:

You give him Amazon’s official signature sample
→ rpm --import ...

Step 2:

You give him Amazon Corretto shop address
→ curl -Lo ... corretto.repo

Step 3:

You tell him to go there and bring Java 17 kit
→ yum install -y java-17-amazon-corretto-devel

Final simple summary

These commands do 3 things:

Import Amazon’s trust key

Add Amazon Corretto repo to yum

Install Java 17 Corretto Development Kit



